WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.920
In the second video of the Quarto Dashboards video series, we're going to talk about dashboard

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:08.920
components.

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:11.600
So, what do I mean by dashboard components?

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:16.299
First of all, let's look at the top of a dashboard, the navigation bar, where we have things like

00:00:16.299 --> 00:00:21.559
the icon or a title for our dashboard, things like an author field if you've added it to

00:00:21.559 --> 00:00:26.719
your YAML, along with links to subpages if we have more than one page to find.

00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:31.680
And by the end of this video, we are going to create a dashboard with two subpages in

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:32.680
it.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:37.200
After our navigation bar on top, we can add further content into the dashboard.

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:39.200
We do this in rows and columns.

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:44.080
We do those with markdown headings, and we can add optional attributes to control the

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:48.200
height of your rows or the width of your columns.

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:52.799
Sidebars are mostly used for interactive input, so if you have an interactive dashboard, that's

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:57.279
where some of your widgets that your users can interact with can go, but they can also

00:00:57.279 --> 00:01:04.519
be useful for overall information about your dashboard or drawing the attention of your

00:01:04.519 --> 00:01:08.099
audience to a particular part of your dashboard as well.

00:01:08.099 --> 00:01:13.239
And then to further divide content, we can use columns inside of rows as well as tab

00:01:13.239 --> 00:01:14.559
sets as well.

00:01:14.559 --> 00:01:19.760
And finally, the content of your dashboards generally live in cards.

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:22.760
So these are containers for code cell outputs.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:28.480
It could be a plot, a table, a value box, as well as free markdown text.

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:33.559
The content of the cards typically maps to executable cells in your notebook or your

00:01:33.559 --> 00:01:37.599
source document, but they could be coming from other things as well, like the markdown

00:01:37.599 --> 00:01:40.279
text we mentioned.

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:46.680
Throughout this video, I'm going to give some examples of dashboard components and layout

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:48.760
and what might go into these cards.

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:51.559
So we are going to see some code cells as well.

00:01:51.559 --> 00:01:57.320
The examples will primarily feature R code, but all of the code in these cells can be

00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:02.660
replaced with a Python version, a Julia version, or an observable version, and the layout would

00:02:02.660 --> 00:02:07.279
look exactly the same, except in a couple places, particularly when we get to value

00:02:07.279 --> 00:02:13.720
boxes, I'll call out that to do something that we are first shown in R in Python, we

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:15.759
may need slightly different syntax.

00:02:15.759 --> 00:02:20.199
So we'll have callouts for those, for those of you following along in Python.

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:24.600
All right, let's start with navigation bar and pages.

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:27.320
So here's a dashboard in a QMD file.

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:33.960
I have on top my YAML with a title, it's called pages, and then format dashboard, since that's

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:38.360
all we need for a QMD file to render to a dashboard.

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:41.119
And then we can see that we have first level headings.

00:02:41.119 --> 00:02:44.759
So one of them is called scatter and the other one is called bar.

00:02:44.759 --> 00:02:50.539
When we render this, we can see that those first level headings map onto pages in my

00:02:50.539 --> 00:02:52.020
dashboard.

00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:57.559
So here's page one, here's page two, and in the first video, we've seen that when we actually

00:02:57.559 --> 00:03:02.880
give names to these headings at the second level for rows and columns, those don't get

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:06.399
reflected in our dashboard, but page names actually do.

00:03:06.399 --> 00:03:10.919
So those words will go on your navigation bar.

00:03:10.919 --> 00:03:15.479
And then another thing that could go in the navigation bar is a logo, and that's something

00:03:15.479 --> 00:03:17.600
we define in our YAML.

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:22.880
So I've defined that underneath dashboard in my YAML, and I'm referring to a local image

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:27.199
in this case, because we're working with the cars dataset, I picked the picture of one

00:03:27.199 --> 00:03:30.020
of my favorite cars, a little beetle.

00:03:30.020 --> 00:03:36.059
So we can see that that is coming from the images folder, and it's, Corto is doing the

00:03:36.059 --> 00:03:37.580
right thing to size it.

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:41.300
So you don't need to do anything for that.

00:03:41.300 --> 00:03:45.740
Other things we can add to our navigation bar are other buttons.

00:03:45.740 --> 00:03:47.460
For example, social buttons.

00:03:47.460 --> 00:03:51.460
Here I have buttons to GitHub, to LinkedIn and YouTube.

00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:54.800
We can see that we're using bootstrap icons for them.

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:59.520
So that's when we say icon, column, GitHub, for example, that's what it's looking for.

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:04.899
We then have an href to where we want that link to go, and we can also add an accessible

00:04:04.899 --> 00:04:07.139
label to them as well.

00:04:07.139 --> 00:04:08.139
And here we go.

00:04:08.139 --> 00:04:14.139
We can see those three social buttons, and Corto is doing some like default styling to

00:04:14.139 --> 00:04:17.179
move them to the other side of the navigation bar.

00:04:17.179 --> 00:04:22.619
As you can imagine, anything is customizable, and we're going to talk about sort of styling

00:04:22.619 --> 00:04:28.079
and customizing the style of your Corto dashboards in our third video.

00:04:28.079 --> 00:04:32.739
But for now, we're going to stick with the default layout for these things.

00:04:32.739 --> 00:04:37.980
For some of the social links, we actually have special aliases for them.

00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:42.820
So that's LinkedIn, Facebook, Reddit, Twitter, and GitHub, things that we've assumed to be

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:44.559
the most commonly used.

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:49.540
So in that case, you can actually list them as a list in nav buttons and then give their

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:54.859
URLs individually, referring to the particular icons that we're pulling in.

00:04:54.859 --> 00:04:59.839
Next, let's talk a little bit about sidebars, rows, columns, and tab sets.

00:04:59.839 --> 00:05:05.480
So sidebars are going to be for information about the dashboard or your data, or as we

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:09.079
said earlier, for user inputs and interactive dashboards.

00:05:09.079 --> 00:05:13.200
They can be at the global level, so shared across each of your pages, or they can be

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.559
at the page level as well.

00:05:15.559 --> 00:05:21.839
To have a global sidebar, we define it just like we would define a page, so with a first-level

00:05:21.839 --> 00:05:29.679
header, but we are denoting the class to be sidebar in curly braces with .sidebar.

00:05:29.679 --> 00:05:36.079
And then I have some text here that's going to be reflected in the sidebar of my dashboard,

00:05:36.079 --> 00:05:37.679
as we can see here.

00:05:37.679 --> 00:05:43.040
And if I scroll over to the other page, we're seeing that the same sidebar is available

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:44.640
there.

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:51.959
For a page-level sidebar, we can then leave the page label as a first-level heading.

00:05:51.959 --> 00:05:57.000
And then inside of that, we're using a second-level heading for our sidebar with the same class

00:05:57.160 --> 00:05:59.959
and the same text available here.

00:05:59.959 --> 00:06:06.119
So here we can see that that sidebar is available on our scatter page, but it's not on our other

00:06:06.119 --> 00:06:09.839
page on the dashboard.

00:06:09.839 --> 00:06:13.260
By default, your cards are going to be laid out in rows.

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:19.079
So when we give Corto Dashboard second-level headings, the first one is going to be row

00:06:19.079 --> 00:06:21.640
1, and the second one is going to be row 2.

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:25.320
So we can see that these cards are basically laid out in those rows.

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:31.399
And once again, the words scatter and bar do not appear on our dashboard.

00:06:31.399 --> 00:06:36.559
Those are things that I personally prefer to give meaningful names to so I can navigate

00:06:36.559 --> 00:06:44.679
my QMD document nicely, but they're not meant to be reflected to your users.

00:06:44.679 --> 00:06:49.440
Another way of saying by default your cards are laid out in rows is to say that the default

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:53.980
value of the orientation field in your YAML is rows.

00:06:53.980 --> 00:06:57.339
So we could add that, and we would get the same result.

00:06:57.339 --> 00:07:03.119
And if we switch that to columns, that makes each second-level heading a column instead

00:07:03.119 --> 00:07:04.220
of a row.

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:09.260
So in this case, those second-level headings for scatter and bar create two cards that

00:07:09.260 --> 00:07:13.640
are placed next to each other across two columns.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:20.619
So one way of designing your dashboard would be first divided into rows and then to columns.

00:07:20.619 --> 00:07:27.220
So in this case, your second-level heading is going to define a row, the overview row.

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:32.700
And then inside of that, we're going to have third-level headings that define columns.

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:36.940
And similarly, the second row is going to be plots.

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:40.799
And inside of that, we're going to have a scatter plot and a bar plot.

00:07:40.799 --> 00:07:45.980
So this is what a four-quadrant dashboard created like this would look like.

00:07:45.980 --> 00:07:53.700
If we wanted to do columns and then rows, we would set the orientation to columns.

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:57.459
And then the second-level headings are going to define your columns.

00:07:57.459 --> 00:08:01.760
And inside of that, the third-level headings are going to define your rows.

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:08.859
So we can see that overview is going to be one column with two rows inside it, some text,

00:08:08.859 --> 00:08:11.500
and then an image.

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:15.720
And plots is going to be the second column with two rows inside it.

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:20.119
That's going to be two plots on top of each other.

00:08:20.119 --> 00:08:23.880
We can then set the heights and widths of our rows and columns.

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:28.480
So here, I have set the orientation as default.

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:30.760
So that's going to be rows first.

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:33.340
So overview and plots create some rows.

00:08:33.340 --> 00:08:35.760
The first one is of height 30%.

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:38.880
The second one is taller, 70%.

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:44.799
And inside of the first row, we have two columns split 20% and 80% in width.

00:08:44.799 --> 00:08:51.039
And inside of the second row, we have two columns split 75% and 25% in width.

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:54.799
So you end up with something like this.

00:08:54.799 --> 00:09:01.119
We've seen that each row in a dashboard that's not given an explicit height will determine

00:09:01.119 --> 00:09:07.679
its size by either filling the available space or by flowing to its natural height.

00:09:07.679 --> 00:09:10.039
The filling layout is generally the default.

00:09:10.039 --> 00:09:15.000
But for certain types of content, for example, when you have marked-down text, flow layout

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:16.000
is the default.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:21.559
If the default behavior is not what you want, you can explicitly specify filling or flowing

00:09:21.559 --> 00:09:25.960
by using the .fill or .flow classes applied to a row.

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:33.799
And you can also apply another class, either at the dashboard level or at a page level.

00:09:33.799 --> 00:09:35.159
Scrolling could be set to true.

00:09:35.159 --> 00:09:39.520
So this is to accommodate any sort of page overflow if things are simply not fitting

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:40.840
into your page.

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:47.039
I should note, though, that while this option is handy for adding many, many more rows of

00:09:47.039 --> 00:09:52.520
cards to a dashboard, spreading these across pages and tab sets can be a better way to

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:54.559
present information.

00:09:54.559 --> 00:09:58.679
Oftentimes when we're looking at a dashboard, it's sort of like you're looking at a printed

00:09:58.679 --> 00:09:59.679
poster.

00:09:59.679 --> 00:10:03.140
You expect things to fit in that one screen.

00:10:03.140 --> 00:10:08.280
And if more depth is needed, you look for those across pages or tab sets as opposed

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:11.320
to scrolling down on that dashboard.

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:15.679
Orientation and scrolling can be provided at the dashboard level, which would mean that

00:10:15.679 --> 00:10:19.719
those would be set at the YAML or at the page level as well.

00:10:19.719 --> 00:10:25.880
So here I'm defining, for example, orientation rows or orientation columns and then scrolling

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:28.799
true in addition to that as well.

00:10:28.799 --> 00:10:33.039
To divide content further, we said tab sets could be handy.

00:10:33.039 --> 00:10:38.280
In order to do that, we would define a tab set class that is associated with a heading.

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:44.000
So here we have two headings, Overview and Plots, that are both set as tab sets.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:49.280
And we can see that inside of my first row, I have two tabs.

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:55.239
Those are my third level headings, Objective and Car, being translated to two tabs in my

00:10:55.239 --> 00:10:56.559
dashboard.

00:10:56.559 --> 00:11:04.320
And similarly, in my Plots row, I have Scatter and Bar that end up being the titles for the

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:08.239
tabs for that second row.

00:11:08.239 --> 00:11:15.179
And finally, let's talk about cards, sort of the primary building blocks of a dashboard.

00:11:15.179 --> 00:11:20.039
These are, as I said, the fundamental unit of display, and they are created automatically

00:11:20.039 --> 00:11:26.460
for cells, computational cells, and also markdown content that are within rows and columns.

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:29.320
So you don't have to say, I want a card here.

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:33.700
You get the cards for free, and then you can further control their behavior.

00:11:33.700 --> 00:11:39.140
But if you would like to manually create a card, you can also do that with a fence div

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:40.140
as well.

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:45.820
So that's three colons, and then the card class applied to that.

00:11:45.820 --> 00:11:50.179
Cards can provide an expand button, which appears at the bottom right on Hover, and

00:11:50.179 --> 00:11:54.619
that will allow you to sort of make that card bigger, which can be really handy if you have

00:11:54.619 --> 00:12:00.419
a detailed plot or a table that is originally taking up only a little bit of space in your

00:12:00.419 --> 00:12:04.780
dashboard, but you want it to be able to zoomable.

00:12:04.780 --> 00:12:12.380
So here we have some computational cells, and the card titles can be provided as a cell

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:14.260
option to that.

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:19.799
Or if you would like to computationally generate those card titles, we could use a function

00:12:19.799 --> 00:12:22.940
like cat in R or print in Python.

00:12:22.940 --> 00:12:24.099
So let's take a look at this.

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:30.380
So in this particular code cell, we've given the card title as a code cell option that

00:12:30.380 --> 00:12:33.380
is following the hash pipe.

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:37.020
So that's title colon highway versus city mileage.

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:40.000
That's going to be the title for that first card.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:46.219
In the second card, we are first calculating how many cars are in this data set by finding

00:12:46.219 --> 00:12:51.580
the number of rows, and then we're writing a cat statement that will put together some

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:53.859
pieces of information.

00:12:53.859 --> 00:12:59.260
The first element is title equals, so that's going to be something that your computational

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:03.820
cell needs to emit so that it can be picked up by Corto.

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:09.380
Then we have some text, drive types of, and then we're basically pasting together the

00:13:09.380 --> 00:13:15.140
number of cards that's calculated and then followed by the word cars.

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:22.419
So we can see that in the first cell, the highway versus city mileage appears as a title,

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:28.460
and in the second cell, the number 234, which is the number of rows that's calculated, is

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:33.700
being used in the title of the cell.

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:37.700
All right, time for a pop quiz to see if you've all been following.

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:38.700
Let's take a look at these.

00:13:38.700 --> 00:13:42.419
Which of these is going to become a card in a dashboard?

00:13:42.419 --> 00:13:47.979
Remember that we said we get cards for free, but in order to get cards, what do we need?

00:13:47.979 --> 00:13:50.419
We need an output to be emitted.

00:13:50.419 --> 00:13:55.700
I'll give you a second to stare at these options, and let's take a look at them.

00:13:55.700 --> 00:13:58.940
In A, we're loading a package.

00:13:58.940 --> 00:14:03.140
That's not going to emit anything, so that's not going to result in a card.

00:14:03.140 --> 00:14:07.659
In B, we're assigning the value 2 to X.

00:14:07.659 --> 00:14:10.340
That's not going to emit anything either.

00:14:10.340 --> 00:14:16.979
In C, we actually have a plot that we're generating, so this will result in an output,

00:14:16.979 --> 00:14:20.380
which then will be placed in a card, so that was the right answer.

00:14:20.380 --> 00:14:26.099
And in D, we have an arithmetic operation, 2 plus 2, that should result in an output

00:14:26.099 --> 00:14:27.979
as well, the number 4.

00:14:27.979 --> 00:14:34.260
However, note that we have set output to false for this particular code cell, so that's not

00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:36.340
going to result in a card either.

00:14:36.340 --> 00:14:40.739
That can be a helpful tool when you're trying to troubleshoot.

00:14:40.739 --> 00:14:46.099
I wouldn't necessarily recommend a bunch of code cells that have output set to false.

00:14:46.099 --> 00:14:51.900
You should, I think, divide them up so that each code cell that generates an output should

00:14:51.900 --> 00:14:55.580
actually result in a card that's being used by your dashboard.

00:14:55.580 --> 00:15:00.700
However, during the development process of your dashboard, it can be handy to turn output

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:06.539
off by setting it to false, just so you can see how layout of certain components might

00:15:06.539 --> 00:15:08.140
look like, for example.

00:15:08.140 --> 00:15:12.979
If a cell generates multiple outputs, they are going to get wrapped in a single card.

00:15:12.979 --> 00:15:14.700
So let's take a look at this cell.

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:21.780
I'm making a plot and then another plot as well, and both of these end up in a single

00:15:21.780 --> 00:15:24.260
card.

00:15:24.260 --> 00:15:29.840
If you want, you can further control the layout of these two plots.

00:15:29.840 --> 00:15:35.020
So we can use the layout and call option, which is an option that's available in Cordo

00:15:35.020 --> 00:15:40.260
outside of dashboards as well, that tells us how to lay out the outputs.

00:15:40.260 --> 00:15:46.619
But in a dashboard setting, that will still keep the output plot inside of the card, but

00:15:46.619 --> 00:15:50.919
lay them out one next to each other or across two columns.

00:15:50.919 --> 00:15:53.739
So this is what that would look like.

00:15:53.739 --> 00:15:55.359
And finally, value boxes.

00:15:55.359 --> 00:16:01.340
These are pretty commonly used in any sort of dashboard, so they're available in Quarto

00:16:01.340 --> 00:16:02.979
dashboards as well.

00:16:02.979 --> 00:16:06.500
They're a great way to prominently display simple values.

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:14.840
You can create value boxes with executable code cells or in plain markdown divs as well.

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:20.500
Value boxes use bootstrap icons, so whatever is available in bootstrap icons will be available

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:23.780
for you to use in your value boxes as well.

00:16:23.780 --> 00:16:28.659
And they can be set to any color, so you can give it some of the color names that Quarto

00:16:28.659 --> 00:16:34.140
will recognize or a hex code, or you can use one of the color aliases that's defined by

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:35.140
your theme.

00:16:35.140 --> 00:16:39.460
So we're going to talk more about themes in our third video, but you've probably seen

00:16:39.460 --> 00:16:44.979
if you've worked, for example, with Quarto and added some callouts to a simple document

00:16:44.979 --> 00:16:50.739
you may have created, you're probably familiar with what info versus warning versus danger

00:16:50.739 --> 00:16:55.820
might look like, and you can also leverage those colors as well.

00:16:55.820 --> 00:17:02.280
This is what value boxes would look like in a Quarto dashboard with R code being used

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:04.079
in executable cells.

00:17:04.079 --> 00:17:11.199
So here we are defining a row with a height of 25% to put our value boxes.

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:15.680
Generally, we don't want them spanning a huge amount of height in our dashboard.

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:17.959
They can, I think, take a little bit of space.

00:17:17.959 --> 00:17:21.140
That's why we've only set them to 25%.

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:25.439
And then I have an executable cell where I'm doing a little bit of calculation.

00:17:25.439 --> 00:17:34.000
So for example, the lowest city mileage car, I'm trying to pull out what that mileage is.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:38.180
As well as the highest one as well, and then also the average.

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:46.599
So we have three values calculated that we're then going to use in our value boxes.

00:17:46.599 --> 00:17:51.760
